<br>
The NLB article discusses the wall temperature, absortion, cooling rates required for various core temperatures. Fortunity it gives the figures in tables, calculating radiation transport requires multi-variable multi-degree diferential equasions that I am not willing or able to do right now. In order to help you I need to know how hot you are planning to run the core. Then you can calculate everything else.<br>
<br>
Interestingly it also gives the thicknesses of the bubbles used in all the earlier studies, listing it at an incredibly thin 5mm. They did discuss internal cooling by hydrogen propellant, which was also a component of your design. When I get the core temperature and finish the calculation for flow and wall temperature I will write more on the article so you can use it to develope your plan. <p>&quot;If,&quot; he wispered, &quot;if we could only pick that lock....&quot; - , THE WORLD SET FREE</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=whitestar60>whitestar60</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 48<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/25/02 8:41:13 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=133.topic&index=70>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.b5tech.net/art/b5/vorlonangry.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Possible source for design answers.</span><hr size=1> Sounds like you guys are doing a good job, I just wish I could help. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mauk2>Mauk2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 115<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/25/02 11:51:16 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=133.topic&index=71>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Possible source for design answers.</span><hr size=1> nebobgrenville: OOOOOOH!   You can't see me, but I am drooling over that paper.  <br>
